📋 Your Developer Mental Model — Save This Forever!
🧠 Phase 1 — Requirements Gathering (ALWAYS FIRST!)
Never touch code before understanding the problem!

Ask yourself:

What data needs to be stored?
What roles exist and what can each role do?
What are the relationships between data?
What are the restrictions and security concerns?


🗄️ Phase 2 — Database Design
Key Concepts You Learned:

Concept   	What It Means
Primary Key	Uniquely identifies every row
Foreign Key	References another table's primary key
Normalization	Every piece of data lives in exactly ONE place
1NF	        Columns are atomic, no duplicates
2NF	        No partial dependencies
3NF	        No transitive dependencies
Junction/Bridge Table	Connects two tables with foreign keys
Data Redundancy	Storing same data twice — always avoid!


create a table structure


🔐 Phase 3 — Authentication Design
Key Concepts You Learned:

Concept	                What It Means
REST	                Rules for how frontend and backend communicate via HTTP
JWT Token	        Like a movie ticket — proves who you are without server storing anything
Stateless	        Server remembers nothing — JWT carries the identity
RBAC	                Role Based Access Control — each role sees only their content
Password Hashing	Never store raw passwords — always hash!
Authorization	        What you can DO after you're logged in
Authentication	        Proving WHO you are


jwt flow:
Login → Server creates token with (user_id, role, expiry)
Every Request → Frontend sends token
Server → Reads and verifies token → No database lookup needed!


📦 Phase 4 — Project Setup
Key Concepts You Learned:

Command	                        What It Does
python -m venv name	        Creates virtual environment
source name/bin/activate	Activates virtual environment
pip install package1 package2	Installs packages
pip freeze > requirements.txt	Saves all dependencies
pip install -r requirements.txt	Recreates environment from file



Why Virtual Environment?
Avoids version conflicts between projects
Keeps dependencies isolated and clean
Makes your project reproducible for teammates


📁 Phase 5 — Project Structure

attendance-backend/
├── app/
│   ├── __init__.py          ← Makes folder a Python package
│   ├── main.py              ← Entry point of entire app
│   ├── database.py          ← DB connection logic
│   ├── schemas.py           ← Data validation (IN and OUT)
│   ├── config.py            ← Settings and environment variables
│   ├── models/              ← Database table definitions
│   ├── routers/             ← API endpoints
│   └── auth/                ← JWT and authentication logic
├── .env                     ← Secret keys (NEVER push to GitHub!)
└── requirements.txt         ← All dependencies



🔄 The Real Developer Workflow (No AI Era!)


1. Understand the problem deeply
        ↓
2. Design on PAPER first (database, flow, roles)
        ↓
3. Read OFFICIAL documentation
        ↓
4. Set up project structure properly
        ↓
5. Build in small pieces and TEST each piece
        ↓
6. When stuck → Google exact error message
        ↓
7. Stack Overflow + GitHub Issues are your best friends
        ↓
8. Read other people's open source code
        ↓
9. Break things deliberately to understand them
        ↓
10. Document everything as you go



✅ Our Build Order:

1. database.py      ← Foundation (DB connection)
        ↓
2. models/          ← Walls (Table definitions)
        ↓
3. auth/            ← Furniture (JWT + password hashing)
        ↓
4. schemas.py       ← Shapes (Data validation)
        ↓
5. routers/         ← Doors (API endpoints)
        ↓
6. main.py          ← Roof (Ties everything together)



SQLAlchemy → The ORM — lets you write Python classes instead of SQL queries ✅

psycopg2-binary → You said "interpreting" — actually it's the driver/adapter — think of it like a translator cable between SQLAlchemy and PostgreSQL specifically!



SQLAlchemy (Python ORM)
        ↓
psycopg2-binary (PostgreSQL specific driver)
        ↓
PostgreSQL (Database)


nest step - working with postgres and its connection.

